(850, 0, '2019-10-01 14:33:12', '2019-10-01 14:33:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dr. Jorge Ortiz is an Assistant Professor of Electrical and Computer Engineering at Rutgers University and the Principle Investigator of the Cyber-Physical Intelligence Lab (CyPhyI Lab -- pronounced SciFi Lab). His research is in applied machine learning for sensor-based systems with a focus on sustainability and healthcare. He joined Rutgers in the Fall of 2018. Prior to joining Rutgers, he was a Research Staff Member at IBM Research working on machine learning and the internet of things. In the five years he was at IBM, he attained 12 patents and published in various top academic conferences, journals, and books and was awarded best Poster at IEEE/ACM IPSN ’08, two Best Paper Runner-up awards at Buildsys ’15, Best Paper at ICISSP ’18, and Best Paper Runner-up at IoTDI ’19. He also spent some time in startups.&nbsp; He co-founded a smart-buildings startup named Pangia and a local services startup named VR-Local. He was also an early employee and kernel contributor to&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://spire.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Spire Global</a>, a mini-satellite (cubesat) company. Jorge is a native New Yorker from Queens, NY and attended the Bronx High School of Science (Class of 1999).&nbsp; Jorge also received his BS in computer science from MIT in 2003 and MS and PhD in computer science from UC Berkeley in 2010 and 2013, respectively. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Dr. Jorge Ortiz', 'Dr. Jorge Ortiz is an Assistant Professor of Electrical and Computer Engineering at Rutgers University and the Principle Investigator of the Cyber-Physical Intelligence Lab (CyPhyI Lab -- pronounced SciFi Lab). His research is in applied machine learning for sensor-based systems with a focus on sustainability and healthcare.', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'dr-jorge-ortiz', '', '', '2019-10-16 22:30:26', '2019-10-16 22:30:26', '', 410, 'https://conference.siliconharlem.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=850', 139, 'speaker', '', 0),
