(888, 0, '2019-10-04 17:10:45', '2019-10-04 17:10:45', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Crystal Bonds is a veteran educator in New York City\'s public schools.&nbsp; Currently, she is the Principal of The High School for Math Science and Engineering (HSMSE) at The City College of New York - one of the nine specialized high schools in New York City.&nbsp; She assumed leadership of the school in 2011, after serving for eight years as an Assistant Principal at Brooklyn Technical High School - also one of the nine specialized high schools in NYC.&nbsp; <em>US New and World Repo</em>rt recognized HSMSE as one of the top high schools in the nation and ranked HSMSE among the top high schools in New York City and New York State.&nbsp; In 2012, the <em>New York Times</em> recognized HSMSE as the most diverse public school in New York City.&nbsp; HSMSE has Crystal’s vision to educate the whole child.  In addition to increasing scores and serving the social and emotional needs of every child, she believes in taking already high achieving students and exposing them to more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Crystal also served as a Master Ambassador Principal (MAP). The program was designed for strong school leaders to take on said assignment for a one-year period, sufficient to allow for a sustainable, dramatic improvement in the quality of instruction and administration at the school.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Born and raised in New York, Crystal earned her undergraduate degree in business marketing from the State University of New York at New Paltz and had worked in the corporate world for several years, prior to becoming an educator.&nbsp; She received a master’s degree in education and another in school administration and supervision.  Currently, her doctoral research focuses on the potential benefits for students, whose high schools are on college campuses.&nbsp; Her prior research focused on expanding and retaining participation of African-American and Latino students in gifted programs.&nbsp; Regularly, she participates in focus groups that investigate the growing need for STEM courses in public school systems.&nbsp; The world of STEM and the early identification of gifted and talented youth are her passion, which is where she focuses much of her time, research, and presentations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Crystal is the Past President of the National Consortium for Specialized Secondary STEM Schools,&nbsp; &nbsp; She is also the President of the CLASS Coalition ( Coalition for Leaders of Advanced Student Success) whose goals are to advocate for high achieving low income students as well as strengthen the school to workforce pipeline.&nbsp; Additionally, Crystal serves on many other boards, advisories, and task forces in the educational and STEM fields.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Crystal Bonds', 'Crystal Bonds is a veteran educator in New York City\'s public schools.  Currently, she is the Principal of The High School for Math Science and Engineering (HSMSE) at The City College of New York - one of the nine specialized high schools in New York City.  She assumed leadership of the school in 2011, after serving for eight years as an Assistant Principal at Brooklyn Technical High School - also one of the nine specialized high schools in NYC.', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'crystal-bonds', '', '', '2019-10-16 22:21:03', '2019-10-16 22:21:03', '', 410, 'https://conference.siliconharlem.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=888', 107, 'speaker', '', 0),
(890, 0, '2019-10-05 16:00:04', '2019-10-05 16:00:04', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Malathi Veeraraghavan received her BTech degree from Indian Institute of Technology (Madras) in 1984, and MS and Ph.D. degrees from Duke University in 1985 and 1988, respectively. After a ten-year career at Bell Laboratories, she served on the faculty at Polytechnic University, Brooklyn, New York from 1999-2002, where she won the Jacobs award for excellence in education in 2002. She served as Director of the Computer Engineering Program at U.Va from 2003-2006. Her current research work is on topics in high-speed networking, which includes optical, datacenter, virtual-circuit, and Grid networks, vehicular networks, and future Internet architectures. She holds 30 patents, has over 130 publications and has received six Best paper awards. She served as the Technical Program Committee Co-Ch air for the High-Speed Networking Symposium in IEEE ICC 2013, as Technical Program Committee Chair for IEEE ICC 2002 and Associate Editor for the IEEE/ACM Transactions on Networking. She was General Chair for IEEE Computer Communications Workshop in 2000, and served as an Area Editor for IEEE Communication Surveys. She served as Editor of IEEE ComSoc e-News and as an Associate Editor of the IEEE Transactions on Reliability from 1992-1994.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Dr. Malathi Veeraraghavan', 'After a ten-year career at Bell Laboratories, Malathi Veeraraghavan served on the faculty at Polytechnic University, Brooklyn, New York from 1999-2002, where she won the Jacobs award for excellence in education in 2002. She served as Director of the Computer Engineering Program at U.Va from 2003-2006. Her current research work is on topics in high-speed networking, which includes optical, datacenter, virtual-circuit, and Grid networks, vehicular networks, and future Internet architectures. She holds 30 patents, has over 130 publications and has received six Best paper awards. ', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'malathi-veeraraghavan', '', '', '2019-10-12 05:44:32', '2019-10-12 05:44:32', '', 410, 'http://siliconharlemconf.192.168.1.11.xip.io:8886/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=890', 107, 'speaker', '', 0),
